1114,IssuesEvent,2016-07-07 17:15:36+00:00,17066884,binux/pyspider,1087996,virtuman,,,opened,Capacity / Limit question - anyone have experience running pyspider in docker? ,[],[],0,"Has anyone ever successfully deployed pyspider in docker environment? I see docker compose and sample docker run commands to start everything up, but i'm curious to know what the highest limits of containers that someone was able to run?

we currently run pyspider on bare metal servers and have lots of under-utilized resources available on other servers, so we'd like to switch all scraping infrastructure to Docker.

We currently have supervisord managing our deployment, with this many processes:
1     x PhantomJS
1     x webui
55   x Fetchers
170 x processors
22   x result_workers
_going further beyond that often puts supervisor out of control_

what i'm trying to understand is if we should run all ""modules"" of pyspider a single process per container, or if we should be using the threaded startup option for some of the modules?
If we run 1 per container - wouldn't it create a crazy overhead and is there any benefit to that? I was wondering if possibly running 10 containers with 10 threads in each would make things a lot more manageable from the docker point of view?

Thanks.",{},{}
