1627,IssuesEvent,2017-04-02 22:25:20+00:00,10047126,dgilland/pydash,1251349,dgilland,,,closed,Remove all alias functions,[],[],1,"Time to get rid of aliases to cut down on the multitude of different ways to invoke the same function. This is primarily to help enforce the ""there should be one way to do it"" mantra of Python within other libraries/applications that use pydash. Having the potential for different function names that call the same function can make debugging more difficult and grepping harder since you have to take into account all the aliases of a function to find where it is being used.

Can use Lodash's own [deprecations page](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/wiki/Deprecations) as a guide but I'd like to eliminate *all* aliases.",{},{}
1658,IssuesEvent,2016-09-09 22:39:02+00:00,38114354,heitzmann/gdspy,11862627,rosivda,,,opened,Descriptor improvements / installation instructions,[],[],0,"I would like to propose some improvements to the description of Gdspy and clarifications to the installation instructions.

# GDSPY README

Gdspy is a Python module for creating/importing/merging of GDSII stream files. It includes key libraries for creating complex CAD layouts:
* Boolean operations on polygons (AND, OR, NOT, XOR) based on clipping algorithm
* Polygon offset (inward and outward rescaling of polygons)
* Efficient point in polygon solutions for large array sets

Gdspy also includes a simple layout viewer. Typical applications of Gdspy are in the fields of electronic chip design, planar lightwave circuit design, and mechanical engineering.

## Installation
### Dependencies:
* [Python](https://www.python.org/) (tested with versions 2.7 and 3.5)
* [Numpy](http://www.numpy.org/) (tested with 1.11.1)
* C compiler (needed only if built from source)

### LINUX / OS X
Option 1: Download Gdspy and build from source using the following command:
```
python setup.py install
```
Option 2: Install Gdspy with pip:
```
pip install gdspy
```
### WINDOWS
Option 1: The preferred option is to install Gdspy using pre-compiled binaries that can be downloaded [here](https://github.com/heitzmann/gdspy/releases) for 32-bit or 64-bit systems. First, download a portable [WinPython](https://winpython.github.io/) (tested with WinPython-64bit-3.5.2.2), run the executable to unpack the files to a directory. In the directory, run ""WinPython Control Panel.exe"" and click ""Add packages"". Select the downloaded Gdspy binary executable and click on ""Install packages"".

Option 2: Gdspy can also be built from source using a development environment to compile the boolean extension module using ``` python setup.py install ``` command.",{},{}
1701,IssuesEvent,2017-09-24 17:56:05+00:00,4477733,kevin1024/vcrpy,413772,graingert,,,closed,return (yield from fn(cassette)) works only with python3,[],[],11,"In *vcrpy/vcr/_handle_coroutine.py* you have:
```
import asyncio


@asyncio.coroutine
def handle_coroutine(vcr, fn):
    with vcr as cassette:
        return (yield from fn(cassette))  # noqa: E999
```
This results in 
```
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/vcr/_handle_coroutine.py"", line 7
    return (yield from fn(cassette))  # noqa: E999
                     ^
SyntaxError: invalid syntax

```

Your setup.py claims the package should work with 2.7, which it seems it does not.",{},{}
1708,IssuesEvent,2015-12-06 00:08:59+00:00,4477733,kevin1024/vcrpy,21099,kevin1024,,,closed,Please add vcr.stubs.VCRHTTPSConnection.is_verified,[],[],7,"The HTTPS `is_verified` property is used in some of our tests. I've [stubbed](https://github.com/vmware/pyvmomi/blob/cb87c26aeb1382396adff0ea885b59371bca95c0/tests/__init__.py#L31) out the method for our own tests as a stop-gap measure. I'm not sure what the best fit solution would be for the library in general, but I'm willing to write it and submit a pull request for the change given a bit of guidance on the issue.

