2156,IssuesEvent,2017-03-24 13:36:12+00:00,20101515,giampaolo/psutil,681260,giampaolo,,,closed,disk_usage(path)  confusion,[],[],1,"It appears that disk_usage (path)  does not report the size of the directory tree  in the specified path but instead reports the size of the partition | mountpoint  that contains the path.

This is not what I expected and the current documentation does not describe this behavior:

psutil.disk_usage(path)[source]
_Return disk usage statistics about the given path as a named tuple including total, used and free space expressed in bytes, plus the percentage usage. OSError is raised if path does not exist_. 

I suggest updating the documentation to make it clear  that you do not get the disk used by the 'path'.
Better still, modify code to  actually report the disk used by the path - like du command

Bill",{},{}
2166,IssuesEvent,2017-12-10 17:34:05+00:00,23076316,horazont/aioxmpp,271710,horazont,,,closed,XEP-0045: Handle messages sent to the MUC during join,[],[],4,"Found by @ge0rg via jabbercat/jabbercat#21.

Messages sent with a MUC Room which has not completed the join yet are handled in a weird manner and we need to figure out how to do this right.

Protocol-wise, sending the message should be fine at that time. However, the occupant object for the local occupant isn’t set up properly yet, which leads to a problematic ``on_message`` event.

Possible solutions:

* delay the ``on_message`` event until the history replay has completed. This means that we need a queue for pending ``on_message`` events in MUC and we also need to time this carefully w.r.t. message tracking. Plus handling of join errors (the message should be bounced internally in that case).
* reject attempts to send a message before join has completed.

We only need an ""okay"" solution in aioxmpp. I think I could live with rejecting send attempts before the join has completed; clients should handle this properly anyways.

Thoughts?",{},{}
