4716,IssuesEvent,2017-03-02 18:08:41+00:00,18595716,veox/python3-krakenex,16007435,wwender,,,opened,Using krakenex with a proxy/ behind a proxy,[],[],0,"Currently krakenex will not work with a proxy/behind a proxy without code change cause it's https requests are based on http.client and urllib.

Best would be to have it based on requests. There the system/OS proxy settings are automatically used. 

What I did for krakenex was to change the connection.py. With a proxy at : myserver:1111 it has to be changed from 
self.conn = http.client.HTTPSConnection(uri, timeout = timeout)

to 

self.conn = http.client.HTTPSConnection(""myserver:1111"", timeout = timeout)
self.conn.set_tunnel(uri)",{},{}
4761,IssuesEvent,2015-12-08 23:10:36+00:00,30582779,warner/magic-wormhole,27146,warner,,,opened,web/websocket/JS support,[],[],0,"I'd like to have a web-capable version. My plans are:

* the python clients will continue to use the current HTTP/EventSource protocol (for the Rendezvous Server) and unframed TCP connections (for the Relay/Transit Server)
* teach the Rendezvous and Relay servers to accept WebSocket connections, allowing interoperability between a python-style client and one that uses WebSockets
* write JS versions of the necessary crypto libraries (which will be easier if I manage to get SPAKE2 into libsodium, then enhance some existing JS binding to expose it).
* write JS versions of the wormhole client
* write a Node.js CLI client
* write a Chrome App drag-and-drop client
* (maybe) write a downloadable web-page client. This obviously has significantly different security properties than a client that you download just once (when installing).
",{},{}
4774,IssuesEvent,2011-12-27 21:43:59+00:00,3052955,rvanlaar/djangorecipe,710771,rvanlaar,,,closed,dajngo.fcgi calls runfastcgi() with default options,"[{'name': 'fastcgi', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/rvanlaar/djangorecipe/labels/fastcgi', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'name': 'Fix Released', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/rvanlaar/djangorecipe/labels/Fix+Released', 'color': 'ddffdd'}, {'name': 'Undecided', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/rvanlaar/djangorecipe/labels/Undecided', 'color': 'ffdddd'}]",[],1,"Right now djangorecipe specifies only ""outlog"" and ""errlog"" keyword arguments when calling runfastcgi() which can be suboptimal.
For example by default runfastcgi() uses method='prefork' which leads to the increased memory usage.

djangorecipe should provide some way to specify custom runfastcgi() options

For example use some variable defined in the project settings. I think it's a good place for fastcgi options. Djangorecipe already provides a facility to use one of available settings modules.

I slightly modified djangorecipe and made following changes to djangorecipe/fcgi.py (the same as attached diff):

diff --git a/src/djangorecipe/fcgi.py b/src/djangorecipe/fcgi.py
index 10eef4e..e814d2b 100644
--- a/src/djangorecipe/fcgi.py
+++ b/src/djangorecipe/fcgi.py
@@ -16,7 +16,9 @@ def main(settings_file, logfile=None):
     # Setup settings
     management.setup_environ(mod)

-    options = {}
+    from django.conf import settings
+
+    options = getattr(settings, 'FASTCGI_OPTIONS', {})
     if logfile:
         options['outlog'] = logfile
         options['errlog'] = logfile


In settings.py I've added:

FASTCGI_OPTIONS = {
    'method': 'threaded',
}

It works for me.

Please consider using this diff, or provide some other way to specify custom fastcgi options.

------------------------------------
Imported from Launchpad using lp2gh.

 * date created: 2009-12-03T17:33:04Z
 * owner: redvasily
 * the launchpad url was https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/492005
",{},{}
