8682,IssuesEvent,2018-06-26 04:59:46+00:00,79510167,pypa/pipenv,605277,uranusjr,647025,pypa,closed,Git submodules in docker,"[{'id': 522150494, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1MjIxNTA0OTQ=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pypa/pipenv/labels/bug%20%F0%9F%90%9B', 'name': 'bug 🐛', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': False}, {'id': 743795404, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw3NDM3OTU0MDQ=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pypa/pipenv/labels/dependency%20resolution', 'name': 'dependency resolution', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}, {'id': 729115975, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw3MjkxMTU5NzU=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pypa/pipenv/labels/docker', 'name': 'docker', 'color': '56ff89', 'default': False}]",[],16,"`pipenv, version 11.10.0`

I have a submodule `./dep1` in my git repo and am adding it to pipenv via `pipenv install -e dep1`, which works just fine and adds the line
```
""abc123"" = {path = ""./dep1"", editable = true}
```
to my Pipfile. Then I use a Dockerfile as follows:
```
FROM kennethreitz/pipenv
COPY ./app /app
COPY ./dep1 /app/dep1
CMD python3 start.py
```
where I added the third line, so the submodule is available in the WORKDIR. However, upon `docker build` I am getting the following error 
```
+ pipenv install --deploy --system
Installing -e ./dep1…

Error:  An error occurred while installing -e ./dep1!
./dep1 should either be a path to a local project or a VCS url beginning with svn+, git+, hg+, or bzr+
```
This is unexpected, since ./dep1 *is* a path to a local project, relative to the WORKDIR in the docker image with the Pipfile, which is /app. Am I missing something or is this a bug?",{},{}
8683,IssuesEvent,2018-01-16 15:28:10+00:00,79510167,pypa/pipenv,3578154,argaen,647025,pypa,opened,--deploy only checks for Pipfile/Pipfile.lock consistency (ignoring setup.py dependencies),[],[],0,"Having a Pipfile as:

```
[[source]]

url = ""https://pypi.python.org/simple""
verify_ssl = true
name = ""pypi""

[packages]

""e1839a8"" = {path = ""."", editable = true}

[dev-packages]

""e1839a8"" = {path = ""."", editable = true, extras=[""dev""]}
```

After the Pipfile.lock file is generated, if we modify dependencies in `setup.py` and do a `pipenv install --deploy` it happily installs the dependencies without noticing the dependencies in the source have changed.

The reason is because the `pipfile.hash` [property](https://github.com/pypa/pipfile/blob/master/pipfile/api.py#L96,L99
) checks only for Pipfile contents but, in our case our dependencies are defined in `setup.py`.

For us, expected result would be the command failing because dependencies in `setup.py` and `Pipfile.lock` don't match.

For reference, part of the code where `--deploy` option is implemented: https://github.com/pypa/pipenv/blob/f5b482453f545fee58e3a4322bd9e7759db85f9f/pipenv/cli.py#L1270

Haven't found any issue related so sorry in advance if this is already documented/discussed somewhere",{},{}
8693,IssuesEvent,2017-12-21 18:59:37+00:00,79510167,pypa/pipenv,62736,OddBloke,647025,pypa,closed,pipenv only attempts to resolve dependencies using the latest version,[],[],2,"python-novaclient 2.26.0 depends directly on pbr < 2.0, as well as other Openstack Python packages (e.g. oslo.i18n>=1.5.0) which also depend on pbr. When these other requirements are resolved, the most recent version that matches the version descriptor is installed (in this example, oslo.i18n 3.19.0). Unfortunately, oslo.i18n 3.19.0 depends on pbr **>=** 2.0, so I end up with a dependency resolution error.

There does, exist, however, a set of the dependent packages that will work together (oslo.i18n 3.12.0, for example, would match the oslo.i18n requirement and depends on pbr >= 1.8, so could be installed alongside python-novaclient 2.26.0).

