8754,IssuesEvent,2017-12-04 22:24:34+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,9040944,JPHammonds,647025,pypa,opened,.py filename changes case on OSX when I run 'python setup.py sdist',[],[],0,"So I just learned that Mac OS X is not truly case sensitive.  I was running 
'python setup.py sdist' 
and then testing my distribution and found that one of my files was not importing properly.  When I went to look the file that I was trying to import was camel cased in the bistro where my calls are lower case.
Going back & digging I found that I could look at the file with any case that I want.  When I run the 'python setup.py sdist' I see:

copying xcirculardichro/gui/dataselection/PointSelectionInfo.py -> xcirculardichro-0.8rc2/xcirculardichro/gui/dataselection

Even though the source file is lower case unless I try to access it on the command line with virtually any case that I want.  Went to a colleague and he said yep, Mac by default only looks case sensitive.

So, I am not sure how setup tools is finding the version with the case.  It is possible I started with Camel case and caught this since I program in other languages where that is more common.  Any thoughts on backing out of this or how setup tools may be picking up this different spelling?

",{},{}
8762,IssuesEvent,2017-03-17 12:25:01+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,235410,jleclanche,647025,pypa,opened,Running setup.py build bdist_wheel results in inconsistent hashbangs,[],[],0,"Pulling from HearthSim/UnityPack#33: When building the package with ./setup.py build bdist_wheel, the hashbang is set to the one of the python in the PATH. If that's a virtualenv python, it'd be set to eg. `/home/adys/.local/share/virtualenvs/...`.

If I do `setup.py build bdist_wheel upload --sign`, it distributes that hashbang and doesn't rewrite it upon installation. This led to bad hashbangs being distributed on pypi.

Accoriding to Yhg1s in #python, running just `setup.py bdist_wheel` without build beforehand led to a correct hashbang rewrite.",{},{}
8783,IssuesEvent,2016-01-31 22:10:01+00:00,1446474,pypa/virtualenv,199266,Ivoz,647025,pypa,closed,Please update virtualenv's wheel package to fix building errors on various packages,[],[],3,"Hello, I've been having trouble installing `lxml`, `coverage` and `simplejson` in a virtualenv due to building wheel error, after days of researching I found a solution exposed in this [bug report](https://bugs.launchpad.net/lxml/+bug/1504926) at lxml.

The error explained there can be avoided if using an updated version of `wheel`, in my system I have no problem because I have `wheel==0.26.0` but when inside a virtualenv I always have error's because of the default installed version of wheel `wheel==0.24.0`.

To avoid the error I have to upgrade `wheel` as soon as I create the virtualenv. 

Could anyone help and make that when creating a virtualenv automatically updates all the packages installed within the virtualenv?

Or someone can give me a hand to try to do it my self? Or at least update the `wheel` version packaged within virtualenv?

To clarify this is not a problem with lxml, coverage or simplejson, the problem is in the wheel version.

Thanks",{},{}
