8904,IssuesEvent,2015-01-26 23:43:09+00:00,3998825,edoburu/django-any-urlfield,27983,jonathanpglick,738973,edoburu,opened,Lambda prevents models using this field from pickling,[],[],0,"I'm trying to set up object caching for my Django project but the Any Urlfields I'm using are keeping the python serializer from pickling.  It seems that [this](https://github.com/edoburu/django-any-urlfield/blob/master/any_urlfield/registry.py#L19) use of a lambda is causing it to throw this error:

     Can't pickle <type 'function'>: attribute lookup __builtin__.function failed

Is there a reason that you want to leave this callable?

Could the `lambda` be removed?

    form_field = forms.ModelChoiceField(queryset=model._default_manager.all(), widget=widget)

Or if it needs to be callable, a partial function could work:

    from functools import partial

    def model_choice_field(model, widget):
        return forms.ModelChoiceField(queryset=model._default_manager.all(), widget=widget)
    ....
    form_field = partial(model_choice_field, model, widget)",{},{}
8930,IssuesEvent,2016-03-11 01:38:39+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,655305,lucidfrontier45,779641,Parsely,closed,Identical KafkaClient is created in different process,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],2,"Hi all. I'm working on Simple Task worker that contains a Kafka consumer.
My code is as follows.

```python
from multiprocessing import Process

from pykafka import KafkaClient


class KafkaWorker(Process):
    def __init__(self):
        Process.__init__(self)

    def run(self):
        print(""{} start"".format(self.pid))

        c = KafkaClient(hosts=""127.0.0.1:9091"")
        print(""{}'s client id = {}"".format(self.pid, id(c)))
        topic = c.topics[""test""]
        consumer = topic.get_balanced_consumer(consumer_group='testgroup',
                                               auto_commit_enable=True,
                                               zookeeper_connect=""127.0.0.1:2281"")
        for msg in consumer:
            print(self.pid, msg.value)


w1 = KafkaWorker()
w1.start()
w2 = KafkaWorker()
w2.start()
```
When I run this code, it says

```python
13452 start
13453 start
13452's client id = 139805036298320
13453's client id = 139805036298320
No handlers could be found for logger ""pykafka.balancedconsumer""
Process KafkaWorker-2:
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/lib/python2.7/multiprocessing/process.py"", line 258, in _bootstrap
    self.run()
  File ""/home/du/PycharmProjects/BusyBee/examples/kafka_test.py"", line 19, in run
