9213,IssuesEvent,2016-08-02 17:32:12+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,15566,rhyolight,1039191,numenta,closed,Refactor boosting/inhibition to stand-alone objects,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/subject:algorithms', 'name': 'subject:algorithms', 'color': 'c7def8'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/type:cleanup', 'name': 'type:cleanup', 'color': '006b75'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/type:enhancement', 'name': 'type:enhancement', 'color': '006b75'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic/labels/under-review', 'name': 'under-review', 'color': 'fbca04'}]",[],3,"edit:
we discussed this with @chetan51 back then, I will try to investigate this issue again - if it is possible to extract Boosting/Inhibition functionality from SP/TP to stand-alone classes. 
pros:
* simpler SP/TP/(TM?) code
* code shared among implementations
* code shared among different classes SP/TP,...

cons:
* there are (easy) optimizations for some cases -- with right data-structure, we can optimize (using eg GPU lib) for all cases


----------------------
I think we should (again) create a class `Boosting` (or BoostingStrategy ?) that would take care of the logic of: 
when should it start boosting? 
which columns? 
and how ""strongly"" to boost? 

