9305,IssuesEvent,2015-01-05 16:37:53+00:00,4357216,yourlabs/django-session-security,10394724,b-d-b,1040547,yourlabs,opened,Implicit declaration of nextPing in script.js,[],[],0,"Hey cool author,

I just wanted to open a question related to your implicit declaration of nextPing variable in apply function of sessionSecurity.prototype within the script.js file.

I was just curious, what was your reason for choosing to implicitly define nextPing?  I am looking at the code, and now obviously the ""best practice"" would suggest not doing this, however it raised the question of, ""When exactly is it okay to use the implicit declaration versus explicitly creating the variable within scope?""  This to me is interesting, since I enjoy being a rule breaker myself.

Since it's a ""best practice"", and one that makes sense in most cases, I was wondering if you could walk me through this decision, since maybe this is the exception to the rule.",{},{}
9335,IssuesEvent,2015-11-23 09:34:39+00:00,30921526,mozilla-services/cliquet,67073,almet,1066228,mozilla-services,opened,"Do not edit ""last_modified"" when pushing new data",[],[],0,"One current limitation of the current protocol is that fact that the `last_modified` metadata (on buckets, collections and records) cannot be set from an external source.

For instance, if one wants replicate the data between two instances (origin and destination), when pushing the updates, the `last_modified` field from the origin data will be replaced by a new one defined by the destination.

As such, the data between the two instances cannot be considered equal.

One way to fix this would be to let the client define what the `last_modified` field is, checking for some heuristics: the new `last-modified` cannot be less than the `max(collection)` for instance.",{},{}
