11676,IssuesEvent,2015-12-15 18:49:29+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,1883523,kwlzn,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,leverage pytest's `--confcutdir` option to isolate conftest.py loading within the buildroot,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/in-progress', 'name': 'in-progress', 'color': '009800'}]",[],2,"A user reported an issue where a `conftest.py` living in his home directory was breaking python tests when run via pants.

After a bit of investigation, it appears that pytest apparently has some unexpected behavior wrt conftest.py discovery. The current algorithm will walk upwards in directories from your test until it locates a `pytest.ini`, `tox.ini` or `setup.cfg` file (or until it reaches the root) - deeming that directory the `rootdir` in pytest parlance. From the test dir all the way up to the `rootdir`, all `conftest.py` files therein are fair game. Furthermore, paths which have `conftest.py` files appear to be automatically added to sys.path (see: https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/82).

This means if a user has a directory layout with a buildroot like `/Users/kwlzn/dev/monorepo`, pytest will walk all paths upwards - including the users home directory. If a stray `conftest.py` exists in the homedir it will be loaded/executed producing a ~/conftest.pyc in the process. This seems somewhat undesirable from a repeatability perspective.

pytest has an option called `--confcutdir`:

```
   confcutdir

   Sets a directory where search upwards for `conftest.py` files stops.
   By default, pytest will stop searching for `conftest.py` files upwards
   from `pytest.ini`/`tox.ini`/`setup.cfg` of the project if any,
   or up to the file-system root.
```

which we can use to lock this behavior into the base of the buildroot. this should hopefully improve the 'not on my machine'/repeatability mechanics an.
",{},{}
