12532,IssuesEvent,2018-06-14 13:43:28+00:00,91356408,allenai/allennlp,1308313,joelgrus,5667695,allenai,opened,eliminate `requirements_test.txt`,[],[],0,"yesterday's bad release was due (in large part) to the distinction between `requirements.txt` and `requirements_test`.txt.

briefly, I added a new feature that required a ""new"" dependency, tried to pip install it, saw that it was already there, and so assumed it was already transitively included in our requirements. but it turns out it was actually one of the *test* requirements (which I have installed, but which don't get pip installed). TeamCity didn't catch this either, because it also installs test requirements!

I failed to catch it manually at the ""test pypi test install"" step, so that's bad on me, but our release process shouldn't rely on that sort of manual verification (and anyway it could have been a much more subtle bug).

This is admittedly an edge case, but (I hit it and so) I think it speaks to having *ONE INSTALL PATH*. If our CI system isn't testing the same ""environment"" that's going into our pip package, that's very bad.

(Before we do this we should eliminate the Jupyter dependency from requirements_test.txt)",{},{}
12540,IssuesEvent,2018-08-14 21:27:30+00:00,91356408,allenai/allennlp,1308313,joelgrus,5667695,allenai,opened,make it easier to fine-tune when the pretrained model is only part of the final model,[],[],0,"both @nelson-liu and @csbhagav have needed to do this recently.

in one case, we needed to train a model that used a pretrained `Seq2SeqEncoder`. in another we needed to train just a classification layer at the end of a pretrained `Model`.

we came up with the following hacky workaround:

(1) have the new model take as constructor parameters `pretrained: Model` (or `pretrained: Seq2SeqEncoder`) and also `pretrained_file: str`
(2) respecify the pretrained config as a subconfig for the new model so that it gets instantiated from params correctly
(3) in the new model constructor, if `pretrained_file` is not None, load the weights for that component from the pretrained file
(4) `load_archive` has logic that throws out config keys that are `pretrained_file` (which was put there to deal with the analogous issue for word embeddings), which means that after fine-tuning the resulting model will have all of its weights and won't need to keep around the pretrained file

we should figure out a cleaner, more general way to handle this situation",{},{}
12551,IssuesEvent,2018-06-29 22:42:41+00:00,91356408,allenai/allennlp,3291951,matt-gardner,5667695,allenai,opened,Add a .get() method to Params,[],[],0,Getting a parameter from a `Params` object without popping it is currently annoying and requires accessing the inner `.params` object that should be private.  We should just add a `.get()` method that works.,{},{}
