12755,IssuesEvent,2015-11-10 15:43:44+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,2579676,Grindizer,6117407,deis,opened,Problem routing with kubernetes and Deis 1.11,[],[],0,"Hi everyone, 

I have a really basic setup with 3 nodes running Deis 1.11 on AWS, the nodes are behind an ELB.
My setup is stateless with an RDS and an S3 bucket for the registry.
(I am able to deploy/access/scale an application when fleet is used as scheduler) 

when I install and use Kubernetes for scheduling, I am not able to route to my application anymore, actually I can see the kubernetes services created, an VIP is affected to the service, and I can see my Pods as well, but the virtual IP of the service is only known on the nodes that run at least one pod of my application.

Here a couple of command to explain a bit more, 
(inv is an inventory of my 3 nodes, controller is the kube controller node). 
When I deployed the application with ""scale cmd=2""
```
ubuntu@ip-10-0-8-122:/tmp$ ansible -i inv controller -m shell -a ""./kubectl --namespace=alfred-kube get pods -o wide""
10.0.124.137 | success | rc=0 >>
NAME                       READY     STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE       NODE
alfred-kube-v2-cmd-c8pad   1/1       Running   0          1m        10.0.124.137
alfred-kube-v2-cmd-d1uvz   1/1       Running   0          15h       10.0.150.224

ubuntu@ip-10-0-8-122:/tmp$ ansible -i inv controller -m shell -a ""./kubectl --namespace=alfred-kube get services""
10.0.124.137 | success | rc=0 >>
NAME        LABELS             SELECTOR                    IP(S)           PORT(S)
app-15746   name=alfred-kube   name=alfred-kube,type=cmd   10.100.237.21   80/TCP

ubuntu@ip-10-0-8-122:/tmp$ ansible -i inv controller -m shell -a ""./kubectl --namespace=alfred-kube describe service app-15746 | grep IP""
10.0.124.137 | success | rc=0 >>
Type:			ClusterIP
IP:			10.100.237.21
```
With this config a can only access my service on the 2 node that run my Pod:
```
ubuntu@ip-10-0-8-122:/tmp$ ansible -i inv all -m shell -a ""curl 10.100.237.21 -s""
10.0.150.224 | success | rc=0 >>
404 page not found

10.0.124.137 | success | rc=0 >>
404 page not found

10.0.162.129 | FAILED | rc=56 >>
```

Same test here with scale cmd=1
```
ubuntu@ip-10-0-8-122:/tmp$ ansible -i inv controller -m shell -a ""./kubectl --namespace=alfred-kube get pods -o wide""
10.0.124.137 | success | rc=0 >>
NAME                       READY     STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE       NODE
alfred-kube-v2-cmd-d1uvz   1/1       Running   0          15h       10.0.150.224

ubuntu@ip-10-0-8-122:/tmp$ ansible -i inv all -m shell -a ""curl 10.100.237.21 -s""
10.0.150.224 | success | rc=0 >>
404 page not found

10.0.124.137 | FAILED | rc=56 >>


10.0.162.129 | FAILED | rc=56 >>
```

I actually checked the router mesh configuration and it is correct, it send the traffic to the correct VIP, but the problem seems to be that the the VIP is not known on certain host. 
As a result, since the ELB sends traffic to all nodes, part of my requests return with a  5xx error. 

My setup is rather simple, so I assumed I am doing something wrong, is it a normal behaviour ? or am I missing something ? I would really appreciate a hint. 

Thanks",{},{}
12759,IssuesEvent,2015-06-17 23:08:39+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,3526404,Joshua-Anderson,6117407,deis,opened,Proposal: Client Go Rewrite,[],[],0,"### Client Go Rewrite Outline

#### Packages

**main**: Does initial command line parsing and parses out the command, like `deisctl`
**client**: Parses command options and calls cmd package, like `deisctl`
**cmd**: takes options and works with models and api, somewhat like `deisctl`
**session**: serializes/deserializes user preferences

```
Load() (Session, error)
Save(session Session) (error)
Exists()(bool, error)
```

**api**:
 - raw REST Methods, can optionally take a session object

 ```
 Get(url string, sslVerify bool) (http.Response, error)
 AuthGet(relUrl string, session Session) (http.Response, error)
 Post(url string, body string, sslVerify bool) (http.Response, error)
 AuthPost(relUrl string, session Session) (http.Response, error)
 Delete(url string, body string, sslVerify bool) (http.Response, error)
 AuthDelete(relUrl string, session Session) (http.Response, error)
 ```

**models**:
 - high level api for working with the controller. Example of the `App` object:

```
Apps.Delete(app App) (error)
Apps.Get(id string) (App, error)
Apps.List()([]App, error)

type App struct {
  id string
  owner string
  created time.Time
  updated time.Time
  ...
}

(app) Save() (error)
```

##### Testing:

I plan to a `httptest` server to mock the controller api.
",{},{}
12762,IssuesEvent,2015-05-15 18:08:43+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,536009,carmstrong,6117407,deis,opened,deisctl: Add 'backup' and 'restore' commands,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/deisctl', 'name': 'deisctl', 'color': 'f7c6c7'}]",[],0,"We have the [backup/restore](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/backing_up_data/) docs, but `deisctl` itself should have a backup/restore command to ease this process. We could also back up and restore etcd, which is not something we currently do - we just repopulate them from the database.",{},{}
12771,IssuesEvent,2015-04-24 21:56:33+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1360539,bacongobbler,6117407,deis,closed,surprising effect of changing from go-buildpack to Dockerfile,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/docs', 'name': 'docs', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],2,"I was using the go buildpack and I added a Dockerfile to switch to using that style of build.  I did this in an existing project.

The surprising result is that my containers built fine but the container would not start,  No output from the logs at all.  I eventually found the problem when `deis run <start command>`  succeeded in starting the container with my program inside it but the ""automatic"" deployment did not.

It wasn't being started because the ""dyno type"" had gotten set to web because of the original go build pack and the Dockerfile expected a type of ""cmd.""  `deis ps:scale cmd=1` fixes the problem, but even a warning message might be helpful.",{},{}
12772,IssuesEvent,2015-01-12 16:26:56+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,73019,mboersma,6117407,deis,opened,integration tests should be one go command line,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/testing', 'name': 'testing', 'color': '006b75'}]",[],0,"The integration tests still have a brittle and non-idiomatic invocation that requires executing what is effectively a `setUp` func as a test, before running each other test file one-by-one. It works, so we hadn't gotten around to cleaning it up. but `godep go test -tags integration -v ./...` should work instead of the sequence of commands in the Makefile. This would also allow us to subset the tests with a regex.",{},{}
12781,IssuesEvent,2016-01-22 08:20:36+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1360539,bacongobbler,6117407,deis,reopened,Add auth:whoami endpoint,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/client', 'name': 'client', 'color': 'ff69b4'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/deis/deis/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '009800'}]",[],6,"Hi there,

TL;DR It would be great to add an endpoint for the `whoami` command (or add the new one) and make it return all user's informations from Deis.

Example Request:

```
GET /v1/whoami HTTP/1.1
Host: deis.example.com
Authorization: token abc123
```

Example Response:

```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
DEIS_API_VERSION: 1.7
DEIS_PLATFORM_VERSION: 1.12.2
Content-Type: application/json

{
  ""id"": 1,
  ""last_login"": ""2014-10-19T22:01:00.601Z"",
  ""is_superuser"": true,
  ""username"": ""test"",
  ""first_name"": ""test"",
  ""last_name"": ""testerson"",
  ""email"": ""test@example.com"",
  ""is_staff"": true,
  ""is_active"": true,
  ""date_joined"": ""2014-10-19T22:01:00.601Z"",
  ""groups"": [],
  ""user_permissions"": []
}
```

## Background

We have a platform with multiple, independent Deis clusters. There is an application with API that synchronizes all informations and a plugin for Deis client. It allows developers to manage databases and their backups through that plugin and application.

## The problem

We would like to allow to destroy database only for application's owner and deny it to the contributors. We are using token to authenticate user against Deis cluster and check his permissions, but we are not able to recognize if he is an owner or not.

We don't want to use informations from the local profile file, because it may be manipulated by the user (you can change your local username by editing this file).",{},{}
12794,IssuesEvent,2015-08-11 16:00:18+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1821014,krancour,6117407,deis,closed,"Inaccurate output: executing on ""container""",[],[],9,"```
$ deisctl ssh controller echo foo
Executing 'echo foo' on container 'controller'
