13401,IssuesEvent,2017-09-14 22:54:52+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,16448634,derekbekoe,6844498,Azure,closed,'Permission denied' error after running 'az login',"[{'id': 418938653, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Auth', 'name': 'Auth', 'color': 'd4c5f9', 'default': False}, {'id': 321247994, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}]",[],0,"I have seen the following error after running `az login -u <USER> -p <PASS>`.

The accessTokens.json file is owned by a different user and the current user does not have write permissions.

```
[Errno 13] Permission denied: '/home/ubuntu/.azure/accessTokens.json'
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/azure/cli/main.py"", line 55, in main
    cmd_result = APPLICATION.execute(args)
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/azure/cli/application.py"", line 117, in execute
    result = expanded_arg.func(params)
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/azure/cli/commands/__init__.py"", line 212, in _execute_command
    result = operation(client, **kwargs) if client else operation(**kwargs)
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/azure/cli/command_modules/profile/custom.py"", line 68, in login
    tenant)
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/azure/cli/_profile.py"", line 109, in find_subscriptions_on_login
    self._creds_cache.persist_cached_creds()
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/azure/cli/_profile.py"", line 324, in persist_cached_creds
    with codecs_open(self._token_file, 'w', encoding='ascii') as cred_file:
  File ""/usr/local/az/envs/default/lib/python2.7/codecs.py"", line 878, in open
    file = __builtin__.open(filename, mode, buffering)
IOError: [Errno 13] Permission denied: '/home/ubuntu/.azure/accessTokens.json'
```

You can see that the file owner is root but the current user is 'ubuntu'. So 'ubuntu' doesn't have access to write to the file. It looks like the file owner should be 'ubuntu'.

```
$ id
uid=1000(ubuntu) gid=1000(ubuntu) 
$ ls -la /home/ubuntu/.azure/
total 24
drwxr-xr-x 2 root   root   4096 Aug  3 19:24 .
drwxr-xr-x 9 ubuntu ubuntu 4096 Jul 22 23:26 ..
-rw-r--r-- 1 root   root      2 Aug  3 19:25 accessTokens.json
-rw-r--r-- 1 root   root      5 May 23 23:40 az.json
-rw-r--r-- 1 root   root      5 May 23 23:40 az.sess
-rw-r--r-- 1 root   root    292 Aug  3 19:24 azureProfile.json
```

It makes sense that the file owner is 'root' as to install the CLI globally, `sudo` is required. But then ideally, the owner of the accessToken file should be 'ubuntu' (especially since the file is in the user directory).
",{},{}
13421,IssuesEvent,2018-05-07 04:26:49+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,327028,colemickens,6844498,Azure,opened,"Documented, Tested Examples of Idempotent Resource Creation",[],[],0,"In light of #5006, I think the community would benefit greatly from having canonical examples of how to write scripts to do things like ""ensure resources exist"".

These types of scripts are used all over the place, and having a documented method for idempotent resource creation is table stakes, in my opinion.

Further, I've been personally broken by changes in the CLI, due to the fact that there was either no guidance around this, no testing around it, or both.

Additionally, someone on Twitter indicated that I might be better off using `az resource show` (rather than `az [resource] show` as it would then be more likely to be consistent about how it handles 404s. Which is a great point, and would be a great thing to see written down in some guidance and example bash scripts.

(Apologies if these such examples exist, I've not been able to find them yet!)",{},{}
