13841,IssuesEvent,2017-05-24 18:26:11+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,3521479,mscuthbert,7388996,jupyter,opened,Use tag to set stop_on_error for CodeCell (Enhancement) ,[],[],0,"I use Jupyter notebook w/ Python a lot for writing documentation (which I later use nbconvert on).  One of the problems that arises is that I want to run all cells to compare output to previous output, but I also like to demonstrate ""what *not* to do"", which often raises errors.  These errors mean that Run All does not fully execute the code.

I think that if a standardized way were defined that marked a code cell as expected to error, it would be a big help to me.  I think that Jupyter 5.0's tags could do so.

For instance, in js/codecell.js we find this method fragment:

```
    CodeCell.prototype.execute = function (stop_on_error) {
        if (!this.kernel) {
            console.log(""Can't execute cell since kernel is not set."");
            return;
        }

        if (stop_on_error === undefined) {
            stop_on_error = true;
        }
```

I believe that a fix might be as simple as something like:

```
        if (stop_on_error === undefined) {
            if (cell.metadata.tags !== undefined && cell.metadata.tags.indexOf('expected-failure') !== -1) {
                stop_on_error = false;
            } else {
                stop_on_error = true;
            }
        }
```

Would this be of interest and on the right track?  If so I'm happy to make a pull request.",{},{}
