14596,IssuesEvent,2016-11-04 14:34:15+00:00,26784827,dotnet/core,5092233,radekpribyl,9141961,dotnet,closed,Nuget.config - relative paths not working with dotnet restore,[],[],4,"Hi all,
I'm not sure if the issue is .net core cli or nuget issue but I will try to start here. Our intention is have a shared folder where all nuget packages are restored to. The folder should be referenced relatively as each developer may sync the code from source control into a different folder. We followed instructions available at https://docs.nuget.org/ndocs/schema/nuget.config-file.md 
Let's say we have the following folder structure:

``` txt
D:\TST
└───f1
     └───f2
```

and in folder TST we have nuget.config file. The content of the file is:

``` xml
<?xml version=""1.0"" encoding=""utf-8""?>
<configuration>
    <config>
        <add key=""globalPackagesFolder"" value=""packages"" />
    </config>
    <packageSources>
        <clear />
        <add key=""nuget v3"" value=""https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json"" />
    </packageSources>
</configuration>
```

Based on this config file I would expect the packages to be restored into ""packages"" folder as outlined:

``` txt
D:\TST
├───f1
│   └───f2
└───packages
```

however when running dotnet restore from within the ""f2"" directory the packages folder is created there and the structure looks like:

``` txt
D:\TST
└───f1
    └───f2
        └───packages
```

It means that the ""packages"" folder is specific to a project and cannot be shared. We tried several ways of defining the relative path e.g. ""./packages"" but nothing worked. When specifying the path as absolute one it works fine. 

So is it a problem of dotnet restore or nuget? We are using dotnet core 1.0.0-preview2-003131 

Thanks for any suggestion.
Radek
",{},{}
14605,IssuesEvent,2018-06-26 19:56:15+00:00,26784827,dotnet/core,2212879,leecow,9141961,dotnet,closed,No AccountController and ManageController from auth Individual template,[],[],1,"# No AccountController and ManageController from auth Individual template

Template

```
dotnet new mvc --auth Individual
```

no longer provides `AccountController` and `ManageController`.

## Description

With host version 2.0.5 this template generates those controllers and with host version 2.1.0 it does not. See the listings below.

### Host 2.0.5

```
$ dotnet --info
.NET Command Line Tools (2.1.4)

Product Information:
 Version:            2.1.4
 Commit SHA-1 hash:  5e8add2190

Runtime Environment:
 OS Name:     Mac OS X
 OS Version:  10.13
 OS Platform: Darwin
 RID:         osx.10.12-x64
 Base Path:   /usr/local/share/dotnet/sdk/2.1.4/

Microsoft .NET Core Shared Framework Host

  Version  : 2.0.5
  Build    : 17373eb129b3b05aa18ece963f8795d65ef8ea54
```

Folder structure after `dotnet new mvc --auth Individual`:

```
$ tree
.
├── Controllers
│   ├── AccountController.cs
│   ├── HomeController.cs
│   └── ManageController.cs
...
```

### Host 2.1.0

```
$ dotnet --info
.NET Core SDK (reflecting any global.json):
 Version:   2.1.300
 Commit:    adab45bf0c

Runtime Environment:
 OS Name:     ubuntu
 OS Version:  16.04
 OS Platform: Linux
 RID:         ubuntu.16.04-x64
 Base Path:   /usr/share/dotnet/sdk/2.1.300/

Host (useful for support):
  Version: 2.1.0
  Commit:  caa7b7e2ba

.NET Core SDKs installed:
  2.1.300 [/usr/share/dotnet/sdk]
```

Folder structure after `dotnet new mvc --auth Individual`:

```
$ tree
.
|-- Controllers
|   `-- HomeController.cs
...
```

## Question

Was this change intentional?
If yes, then how does one gets those controllers generated with host version 2.1.0 (or later)?
If no, then I guess it is a bug.

*If I chose the wrong tracker to report this issue, sorry for that and please guide me to the right one.*",{},{}
