14642,IssuesEvent,2018-04-11 16:39:03+00:00,26784827,dotnet/core,1253414,divega,9141961,dotnet,closed,Inconsistent collection navigation property projection,[],[],2,"I have the following in latest versions of EF Core:

```
var entityOnes = await dbContext.EntityOnes.Where(blah)
    .Include(a => a.EntityTwos)
    .Include(a => a.EntityThrees)
    .ToListAsync();
```

After this executes, the following works fine, as expected:

```
var test = entityOnes[0].EntityTwos[0].EntityThrees[0];
```

However, the following could possibly throw a null exception because the `EntityThrees` property is null:

```
var test = entityOnes[0].EntityTwos[1].EntityThrees[0];
```

It seems like the `EntityThree` collection property only gets set if there are values to add to the collection.  If the collection is empty, then it leaves the property null.

This seems like inconsistent behavior to me.  I'm initializing these properties as null as a safeguard to let me know if EntityFramework has already projected values onto the relationship or not.

For example, if the following throws a null exception, then I know that I forgot to add EntityTwo as an Include() in EF query:
```
var test = entityOnes[1].EntityTwos[0];
```
",{},{}
14655,IssuesEvent,2018-01-14 20:38:11+00:00,26784827,dotnet/core,8228359,Petermarcu,9141961,dotnet,closed,Debug.Assert causing an application to crash.,[],[],0,"# Issue Title

Debug.Assert causing an application to crash.

# General

Typically, Debug.Assert should bring a pop-up with Abort, Retry, Ignore, or if the `assertuienabled` property is `false` then it should just continue, however in version 2.1.2 hitting the assert is causing the app to crash with a `FailFast` message.

For a simple console app:
```C#
using System;
using System.Diagnostics;

namespace ConsoleApp1
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(""Hello World!"");
            Debug.Assert(false, ""Assert hit"");
            Console.WriteLine(""Goodbye World!"");

        }
    }
}
```

You get this:
```
C:\Users\anpaz\source\repos\ConsoleApp1\ConsoleApp1>dotnet run
Hello World!
FailFast: Assert hit

   at System.Diagnostics.Debug.Assert(Boolean condition, String message, String detailMessage)
   at ConsoleApp1.Program.Main(String[] args) in C:\ConsoleApp1\ConsoleApp1\Program.cs:line 11

   at System.Environment.FailFast(System.String, System.Exception)
   at ConsoleApp1.Program.Main(System.String[])
```

I'm finding this to be problematic in my xUnit tests: when I run the tests and they (purposely) hit a Debug.Assert the run pauses and eventually fails.

```
> dotnet --version
2.1.2
```
",{},{}
