14750,IssuesEvent,2016-01-24 09:44:10+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,14043887,JohnDenker,9289019,letsencrypt,opened, renewal notice : email should sequence the domain names correctly,[],[],0,"#### Background

Suppose a certificate was created using a command of the form
> letsencrypt-auto run -d www.example.com -d example.com ....

Note the order in which the domain names appear.

#### Observed behavior

The renewal email mentions the relevant domain names in some wacky order:
> example.com, www.example.com

#### Desired behavior

* It should mention them in the correct order ... at least with the correct name first.  This is important, because the certificate files are named after the **first** domain name mentioned on the command line, as discussed in item #1376.

* The email should be even more explicit:  It should say like:
> To renew the same set of domain names, pass the following options on the command line:
> -d www.example.com -d example.com
",{},{}
14760,IssuesEvent,2016-01-09 00:44:45+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Doesn't understand `ssl on` directive,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/nginx', 'name': 'nginx', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],3,"In Nginx there are two ways to turn on SSL for a server:

```
server {
  listen 443 ssl;
}
```

```
server {
  listen 443;
  ssl on;
}
```

Our Nginx plugin doesn't understand the latter. In parser.py's `get_vhosts`, the `VirtualHost` object will be created with `ssl = False`, leading later code to attempt to ""enable"" SSL on that vhost, creating a fatal conflict for the ssl_certificate directive. One possible easy fix: Look for `ssl_certificate` to determine whether a vhost has ssl enabled, instead of looking at the `listen` or `ssl` directives.",{},{}
