15109,IssuesEvent,2015-03-17 05:35:10+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,3112159,taion,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,Determining when serializing many in data handler,[],[],0,"I don't see a way to explicitly determine when we are serializing many objects in the data handler. It's not sufficient just to check `schema.many` because I may be calling `schema.dump(objs, many=True)`.

Looks like right now the only way I can e.g. reliably add extra fields per serialized object without having to guess whether the data represents many objects is by overriding `Schema._postprocess` per the example, but this seems like it should really be possible with just data handlers.",{},{}
15126,IssuesEvent,2016-02-17 08:20:26+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,728628,bereal,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,Method hooks swallow AttributeError,[],[],0,"If `AttributeError` is raised by a `Method`/`Function` hook, it is silently swallowed:

    class C(Schema):
        f = fields.Method('_bad_serialize')
        def _bad_serialize(self, obj):
            return self._do_something_else(obj)  # raises AttributeError

    test_type = namedtuple('test_type', 'f')
    C(strict=True).dump(test_type(123))  # returns empty list

This makes finding the bugs harder. I understand the rationale and I guess fixing it might make some code backward incompatible, but is there a way to add at least some warning mode?",{},{}
15136,IssuesEvent,2018-06-13 00:38:24+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,RFC: Remove `field_name` and `fields` attributes from ValidationError,[],[],0,"Currently, `ValidationError` stores the field name and field instances associated with the error.

```python
from marshmallow import Schema, fields

class MySchema(Schema):
    foo = fields.Int()

schema = MySchema()
try:
    schema.load({'foo': 'invalid'})
except Exception as error:
    print(error.field_names)  # ['foo']
```

I propose removing these attributes because they are redundant with the data in `ValidationError.messages` and they unnecessarily complicate the validation logic.

`fields` and `field_names` were [added](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/commit/cbc199af077e710f0cd7efd370be86ff857e0d18) at a time (version 1.1.0 😓 ) when it was impossible to access all the error messages for a schema (see #63). It wasn't [until 2.0](https://marshmallow.readthedocs.io/en/latest/upgrading.html#accessing-error-messages-in-strict-mode) that it became possible to get the full error messages dict when using strict mode.

At this point, I don't see a use case for accessing `field_names` and `fields`.
",{},{}
15141,IssuesEvent,2018-01-11 12:23:42+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,147901,jakubczaplicki,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,Add support for data URI scheme,[],[],0,"Currently [data URI's](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_URI_scheme) are not supported by `fields.Url` validation. Marshmallow should allow to pass a valid `data:` URI.
E.g. ```data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAUAAAAFCAYAAACNbyblAAAAHElEQVQI12P4//8/w38GIAXDIBKE0DHxgljNBAAO9TXL0Y4OHwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==```",{},{}
15147,IssuesEvent,2016-02-09 04:14:19+00:00,42371441,marshmallow-code/marshmallow-jsonapi,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,closed,pre_load needs to be updated for complete deserialization,[],[],5,"@sloria @cmanallen @micheljung
I'm very much liking marshmallow jsonapi, but it feels like it is only useful for dumping data as a few significant issues have come up with deserialization. See:
#15 - data from relationship (and type) fields is not loaded 
#18 - ma-jsonapi not compatible with webargs parser
#20 - no documentation for deserialization

To focus on #15 and #18; I get the impression that the underlying problem is that the ma-jsonapi schema does not use marshmallow fields for the 1st level jsonapi objects (e.g. relationships, data)

Would using [nested schemas](http://marshmallow.readthedocs.org/en/latest/nesting.html?highlight=nested#nesting-schemas) for the 1st level objects resolve these deserialization issues?

",{},{}
