15597,IssuesEvent,2015-09-01 21:55:31+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,417568,craffel,11752110,Lasagne,opened,lasagne.updates.adam yields float64 updates with float32 0d-array input,[],[],0,"Just tracked down this strange behavior.

```Python
>>> import theano
>>> import lasagne
>>> import numpy as np
>>> import theano.tensor as T
>>> x = theano.shared(np.ones((10,), dtype=theano.config.floatX))
>>> f = T.sum(x**2)
>>> u = lasagne.updates.adam(f, [x], beta2=.99)
>>> print [v.type for v in u.values()]
[TensorType(float32, vector),
 TensorType(float32, vector),
 TensorType(float32, vector),
 TensorType(float32, scalar)]
>>> u = lasagne.updates.adam(
...     f, [x], beta2=np.array(.99, dtype=theano.config.floatX))
>>> print [v.type for v in u.values()]
[TensorType(float32, vector),
 TensorType(float64, vector),
 TensorType(float64, vector),
 TensorType(float32, scalar)]
```

If the resulting updates are passed into `theano.function`, a type error is raised because the update for a `float32` values is `float64`.  In this particular case, what's happening is that in `lasagne.adams.updates`, the following:
```
v_t = beta2*v_prev + (1-beta2)*g_t**2
```
`(1 - beta2)` will be given a dtype `float64`:
```Python
>>> (1 - np.array(0., dtype='float32')).dtype
dtype('float64')
```

So, given this, I think we have three options:

1. Implicitly cast things using `utils.floatX` everywhere, which would make the line in question become
`beta2*v_prev + (utils.floatX(1.)-beta2)*g_t**utils.floatX(2.)` (puke)

1. Convert arguments to updates functions to `float`, because if a float is passed instead of a 0d-array with the correct dtype, everything works out fine thanks to Theano's willingness to cast Python scalars to the correct type

1. Tell users (like me) to obey the RTFM, i.e. `beta2 : float` is specified in the docstring, so if I pass anything else (like a numpy scalar), I'm going to have a bad time.",{},{}
15615,IssuesEvent,2015-10-02 13:10:50+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,closed,TransformerLayer doesn't handle edge pixels properly,[],[],7,"The interpolation in TransformerLayer averages two adjacent pixels to get the interpolated value, and multiplies it by a coefficient that is the distance of the new coordinate from the interpolated coordinates.

The adjacent pixels of the edge pixels are clipped to the same value, and so the coefficient can be zero (in the code it comes down to x = x0 = x1).

The solution I am using now is to scale the coordinates to [0, width - 2] and [0, height - 2] so there are always two adjacent pixels.

I read online that a common solution for edges is take only one closest pixel.
",{},{}
15636,IssuesEvent,2017-06-21 15:29:28+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,closed,"windows or mac platform has  no lasagne v0.2, can you update the version to v0.2. Because I find so much library relys on v0.2, thank you very much.",[],[],2,"Before submitting your issue, please check these hints!

- **If you have a usage question**, please please post on [our mailing list](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/lasagne-users) instead of creating an issue.
  Make sure to check the [Lasagne documentation](http://lasagne.readthedocs.org/en/latest/) and the [Theano documentation](http://deeplearning.net/software/theano/) first!
  You can search the mailing list as well to see if your question has come up before.

- **If you suspect you have found a bug**, please first try [updating to the bleeding-edge versions of Theano and Lasagne](http://lasagne.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user/installation.html#bleeding-edge-version). It may have been fixed already.
  If you are not sure whether the problem lies within your code, Theano, or Lasagne, first post on [our mailing list](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/lasagne-users).
  In any case, try to provide a minimal code example that reproduces the bug, this will greatly speed up the process of tracking down the problem.

- **If you have a feature request or idea**, please include a clear description of the use case(s) it would enable, referencing research papers if applicable, and indicate whether you would be willing to implement the feature yourself.
  We are happy to discuss your suggestion, help refining it, and decide upfront whether it would fit the main library or our [Lasagne/Recipes](https://github.com/Lasagne/Recipes).
",{},{}
