16147,IssuesEvent,2018-04-12 16:48:14+00:00,31315021,Kinto/kinto,17006,glasserc,13413813,Kinto,closed,Why do we restart pagination from the beginning?,"[{'id': 180758578, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Kinto/kinto/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}]",[],7,"While working on #1576, I saw that occasionally we would generate a pagination token that would not match any records (i.e. it was at the very end of the list of objects to paginate). When this happened, the memory backend would restart pagination at the beginning. However, I can't tell if this behavior is intentional or not and what the reasoning for it is.

One reason it might be intentional: you can hit this behavior if someone inserts elements at the beginning of a list you're in the middle of paginating. In that case, restarting pagination from the beginning is the only way to eventually get to all of the items.

One reason it might not be intentional: once you show the first page of objects again, we no longer show a `Next-Page` header, so it's not really ""restarting pagination""; it's ""you get the first page of results again"". This might mean that you never actually see the elements that were inserted, if they were inserted in the middle.",{},{}
