16512,IssuesEvent,2016-12-27 14:38:05+00:00,43056951,graphql-python/graphene,5281987,RaduW,15002022,graphql-python,opened,Incorrect example on mounting scalars (documentation),[],[],0,"The example on [Mounting Scalars](http://docs.graphene-python.org/en/latest/types/scalars/)
reads:

> `graphene.Field(graphene.String, to=graphene.String())`
> ### Is equivalent to:
> `graphene.Field(graphene.String, to=graphene.Argument(graphene.String()))`

(the code above generates an error)
it should read:
> `graphene.Field(graphene.String, to=graphene.String())`
> ### Is equivalent to:
> `graphene.Field(graphene.String, to=graphene.Argument(graphene.String))`
",{},{}
16517,IssuesEvent,2015-10-28 16:04:39+00:00,43769764,graphql-python/graphql-core,327472,faassen,15002022,graphql-python,opened,GraphQLArgument with default_value None,[],[],0,"In wsgi_graphql at https://github.com/faassen/wsgi_graphql I have tests in the test suite when I update to graphql-core. These are caused by the handling of default_value. If you omit `default_value` (which I do in test_wsgi_graphql.TestSchema) it is set to `None`. This now causes error messages in `graphql-core`, which
weren't there in `graphqllib` before, and it doesn't seem to be right in general: the `express-graphql` tests also omit the default value and this works fine.

You can make the tests pass by putting in a `default_value` of `False` explicitly:

```
                args={
                    'who': GraphQLArgument(
                        type=GraphQLString,
                        default_value=False
                    )
                },
```
",{},{}
