17200,IssuesEvent,2016-03-05 16:38:59+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1203629,wjakob,17565521,pybind,closed,Migration from Boost.Python,[],[],1,"I'm considering migrating from Boost.Python to pybind11 for a C++ application that embeds Python3 (Windows platform). Main reason is I would like to get rid of this huge Boost dependency.

The project is nothing fancy in regards to the inter-language connection: exposed C++ classes, heavy use of std::shared_ptr, tied lifetime of C++-Python objects. Exception-protected at inter-language boundaries. Casting of shared_ptr objects, strings, vector, list and map containers. No custodian_and_ward'ish policy.

While it seems pybind11 ""just works"" (tm) and that my use case seems to fit perfectly on paper, it is unclear to me whether it can be considered *stable* enough for such a migration. Would you advise me wait a bit or to start digging?",{},{}
