17680,IssuesEvent,2018-01-19 13:31:35+00:00,118126376,gisaia/ARLAS-server,9483289,elouanKeryell-Even,20204404,gisaia,closed,Dockerfile: add build process,"[{'id': 809961095, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/gisaia/ARLAS-server/labels/To%20Do', 'name': 'To Do', 'color': 'ededed', 'default': False}, {'id': 809961096, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/gisaia/ARLAS-server/labels/To%20Do', 'name': 'To Do', 'color': 'ededed', 'default': False}]",[],0,Add an initial build process in the dockerfile with an initial FROM clause,{},{}
17688,IssuesEvent,2017-11-19 05:11:43+00:00,35988711,tox-dev/tox-travis,15092,jayvdb,20345659,tox-dev,opened,Deprecation of matching undeclared envs,[],[],0,"Apparently we're deprecating a feature I often use, or more likely something else is slightly off.

see https://github.com/vstinner/faulthandler/pull/33/commits/957915c23441a262cd2ee35c667a3dfcaf3b6624 , for adding testing of an environment that *is* declared by tox.  `py26` is a part of the standard `tox` environment list.

However this results in:

> Matching undeclared envs is deprecated. Be sure all the envs that Tox should run are declared in the tox config.

Build showing problem at
https://travis-ci.org/vstinner/faulthandler/jobs/304196356#L487

Irrespective of anything else, there is a very good reason to not require any modification to `tox.ini`.
Many people want `tox-travis` to be only a travis thing, and not need further configuration that they need to see.  Travis testing can include environments that they do not want to see in `tox.ini`, because they dont want `tox` on their workstation to know about (and try to run) non-standard environments.
If `tox-travis` requires modifications to `tox.ini`, you loose users, because they are opinionated about `tox.ini`, but not opinionated about `.travis.yml` as long as it does the job.",{},{}
17690,IssuesEvent,2017-07-11 09:13:07+00:00,1732211,FactoryBoy/factory_boy,483314,jeffwidman,20368050,FactoryBoy,closed,Trait Chaining is not working as mentioned in the docs ,[],[],1,"The Trait Chaining is not working as mentioned in the docs or as it should. When you chain a trait, the parent trait values actually override the child one

For eg

```
class OrderFactory(factory.Factory):
    class Meta:
        model = Order

    # Can be pending/shipping/received
    state = 'pending'
    shipped_on = None
    shipped_by = None
    received_on = None
    received_by = None

    class Params:
        shipped = factory.Trait(
            state='shipped',
            shipped_on=datetime.date.today,
            shipped_by=factory.SubFactory(EmployeeFactory),
        )
        received = factory.Trait(
            shipped=True,
            state='received',
            shipped_on=datetime.date.today - datetime.timedelta(days=4),
            received_on=datetime.date.today,
            received_by=factory.SubFactory(CustomerFactory),
        )
```
In this example borrowed from documentation following assert should work

```
o = OrderFactory.build(received=True)
assert o.state == 'received' 
```
However this is not the case with the latest factory boy version ie `2.8.1`. The value of o.state evaluates to `shipped`.
",{},{}
