17829,IssuesEvent,2017-10-03 10:29:43+00:00,73328905,pytorch/vision,11921406,iacolippo,21003710,pytorch,closed,Inconsistent datatype from train_loader.dataset.train_data,[],[],2,"I've noticed that the type of data contained in the data loaders are different from one dataset to another. For example

`data_loader.dataset.train_data` with CIFAR10 is a `np.array`, while with MNIST it is a `torch.Tensor`

Is this for some reason? 

I think it should be uniformed because I often write code which requires knowing something from the training data and if I want to write it for multiple dataset this is a bit inconvenient.",{},{}
17831,IssuesEvent,2018-01-30 06:03:45+00:00,73328905,pytorch/vision,9110200,fmassa,21003710,pytorch,closed,Dataset target datatypes vary between Datasets,[],[],6,"For example, when using `torchvision.datasets.MNIST`, the targets are returned as type `int`:
```python
>>> torchvision.datasets.MNIST('./data', train=True)
<torchvision.datasets.mnist.MNIST object at 0x7feb5af89860>
>>> ds = torchvision.datasets.MNIST('./data', train=True)
>>> ds[0]
(<PIL.Image.Image image mode=L size=28x28 at 0x7FEB5AF89C18>, 5)
>>> type(ds[0][1])
<class 'int'>
```

But when using the SVHN dataset, they are returned as `numpy.int64`:

```python
>>> ds = torchvision.datasets.SVHN('./data', split='train')
>>> ds[0]
(<PIL.Image.Image image mode=RGB size=32x32 at 0x7FEB5AF89C18>, 1)
>>> type(ds[0][1])
<class 'numpy.int64'> 
```

A minor issue, I'm sure, but one nevertheless. This is because it's possible to turn a list of `int` into `torch.LongTensor`, but not `numpy.int64`:

```python
>>> torch.LongTensor([1,2,3])

 1
 2
 3
[torch.LongTensor of size 3]

>>> torch.LongTensor([np.int64(1),np.int64(2)])
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
RuntimeError: tried to construct a tensor from a int sequence, but found an item of type numpy.int64 at index (0)

```",{},{}
17838,IssuesEvent,2017-03-08 23:30:04+00:00,66363927,zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient,8939758,andy-maier,21196715,zhmcclient,closed,Reduce Travis and Appveyor CIs to process just the PR,"[{'id': 429586455, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient/labels/area:%20devenv', 'name': 'area: devenv', 'color': '207de5', 'default': False}, {'id': 429588767, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/zhmcclient/python-zhmcclient/labels/resolution:%20fixed', 'name': 'resolution: fixed', 'color': 'cccccc', 'default': False}]",[],3,"Right now, the web hooks for Travis and Appveyor are configured to invoke them for both the PR code and for the code when merged. This runs them twice as often without much of a benefit, and causes the elapsed time for the checks to be twice as long.

It seems that many other projects on GitHub that use Travis and Appveyor just run them on the PR code, for example [pip](https://github.com/pypa/pip) or [click-spinner](https://github.com/click-contrib/click-spinner).

Don't know exactly which triggers need to be disabled, but in the PR check list, the following entries must remain:
```
    continuous-integration/appveyor/pr — AppVeyor build succeeded
    continuous-integration/travis-ci/pr — The Travis CI build passed
```",{},{}
