18754,IssuesEvent,2012-02-20 08:31:39+00:00,3342046,RDFLib/rdflib,16417,gjhiggins,1401847,RDFLib,closed,"""table does not exist"" error unconditionally written to stderr",[],[],0,"coryd...@gmail.com, 2009-04-13T18:00:43.000Z
<pre>
Every time you create a new sqlite store, you get a useless error message
written to stderr.  Remove this debug print error message or replace it
with a proper log message.

<b>What steps will reproduce the problem?</b>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1. Run this code::

    def sqliteBackedGraph(path, filename):
        """"""
        Open previously created store, or create it if it doesn't exist yet.
        """"""
        from pysqlite2.dbapi2 import OperationalError
        from rdflib import plugin
        from rdflib import ConjunctiveGraph as Graph
        from rdflib.store import Store, VALID_STORE

        # Get the sqlite plugin. You may have to install the python sqlite
libraries
        store = plugin.get('SQLite', Store)(filename)

        rt = store.open(path, create=False)

        if rt != VALID_STORE:
            # There is no underlying sqlite infrastructure, create it
            rt = store.open(path, create=True)
            assert rt == VALID_STORE
         
        # There is a store, use it
        return Graph(store)

    sqliteBackedGraph('/tmp', 'temp.db')


<b>What is the expected output? What do you see instead?</b>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

This code should print nothing (only create temp.db).  Instead it prints::

    table kb_b0304b8ab6_asserted_statements Doesn't exist

(exact string may vary).

Comment 1 by coryd...@gmail.com
Any problem with me just removing this?  Would be nice to have this change in the
2.4.1 branch.


Comment 2 by eik...@gmail.com
That'd be great. If you can put a brief note in the CHANGELOG too that'd be helpful.


Comment 3 by coryd...@gmail.com
Made this change in both trunk and rdflib-2.4.x branch, with CHANGELOG entries in
both places. (r1663, r1664, r1665, r1666).

MySQL has the same issue but also has *many* stderr prints.  I decided not to touch
that file, since I don't use it and someone else should code review that file.
</pre>",{},{}
18755,IssuesEvent,2012-02-20 08:32:00+00:00,3342046,RDFLib/rdflib,16417,gjhiggins,1401847,RDFLib,closed,JSON serialization/parsing,[],[],0,"azarot...@gmail.com, 2009-07-15T17:41:44.000Z
<pre>
Attached JSON serializer and parser, for consideration.

Comment 1 by eik...@gmail.com



Comment 2 by ed.summers



Comment 3 by lindstr...@gmail.com
Given the current plethora of JSON formats for RDF, can we really endorse this one? It's 
a nice take (seems based on the Google JSON format for Atom/GData), but see also e.g.:

 
  (my own, experimental, works with 
rdflib)

(Furthermore, Google seems to be moving away from their current format to a 
simplified/compact version 
().)

Although I'd very much like to see JSON support in RDFLib, we should take care to 
support only things with a wide adoption, or wait until more consensus (there is interest 
within W3C for this as well).


Comment 4 by azarot...@gmail.com
Why pick and choose?  So long as each format has an identifier, then they can be used
or not as the developer desires. Some better naming system could be used to make the
distinctions easier:  json-(name)  for example.


Comment 5 by ed.summers
Since eikeon is leaning towards bundling additional non-core functionality as 3rd 
party extensions perhaps json serialization/deserialization can be left out of the 
core and distributed separately somehow?


Comment 6 by eik...@gmail.com
Yeah, let's focus on getting the core bits back in order first for Milestone-Release2.5.


Comment 7 by ed.summers
Rob, would you be open to me working with you to bundle this as an extension? I'm 
thinking of putting the code on github/bitbucket or in an extensions svn directory 
here in rdflib svn, adding setup.py, docs, pushing to pypi, and adding an extensions 
page to the rdflib wiki?


Comment 8 by azarot...@gmail.com
@edsu:  Yep, no problem :)


Comment 9 by eik...@gmail.com
Sounds like a great plan guys; thank you. I think we'll all benefit from more distributed development and keeping 
rdflib a little leaner.


Comment 10 by ed.summers
hmm I didn't get much time to spend on packaging up this as an extension. As lindstream said, there are some other more ""standard"" json formats that would make sense to bundle in rdflib. There's nothing that prevents azaroth42 from distributing his rdflib plugin himself. So I'm going to close this one.


Comment 11 by lindstr...@gmail.com
I agree, as expected. ;) There's a lot going on right now on this front, and we should wait to see how the dust settles standardization-wise. Specifically for RDFLib, I've included the Gluon mechanics in the Oort trunk proper for anyone interested (just one of many ways to do it, and gluon *will* get updated as consensus is hopefully approached).


Comment 12 by lindstr...@gmail.com
I should also say that if there's a convergence in the plethora of formats, I expect Gluon to merge with that. If so, I think my parsing and serializing code should be moved from ""Oort"" to rdfextras (considering that for ""incubation"" for possible inclusion in RDFLib once the format is finalized/standardized/""defacto""-ized).
</pre>",{},{}
